{"title_page": "Second Mexican Empire", "text_new": "{{For|the earlier monarchy in Mexico|First Mexican Empire}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox country\n| native_name                = ''Imperio Mexicano'' ([[Spanish language|Spanish]])\n| conventional_long_name                = Mexican Empire\n| common_name                = Mexico\n| status_text                = Protectorate of [[Second French Empire|France]]\n| status                = Empire\n| year_start                = 1864\n| year_end                = 1867\n| p1                = Second Federal Republic of Mexico\n| flag_p1                = Bandera de la Segunda Rep\u00fablica Federal de los Estados Unidos Mexicanos.svg\n| national_motto                = ''Equidad en la Justicia''<br/><small>\"Equity in Justice\"</small>\n| national_anthem                = \"[[Himno Nacional Mexicano]]\"<br/><small>({{lang-en|\"National Anthem of Mexico\"}})</small><br /><center>[[File:Himno Nacional Mexicano instrumental.ogg]]</center>\n| s1                = United Mexican States\n| flag_s1                = Flag of Mexico (1823-1864, 1867-1893).svg\n| image_flag                = Bandera del Segundo Imperio Mexicano (1864-1867).svg\n| flag                = Flag of Mexico\n| image_coat                = Coat of Arms of the Second Mexican Empire.svg\n| symbol_type                = Imperial Coat of arms\n| symbol_type_article                = Coat of arms of Mexico\n| image_map                = Second Mexican Empire (orthographic projection).svg\n| image_map_caption                = Territory of the Second Mexican Empire upon establishment\n| capital                = Mexico City\n| common_languages                = Spanish\n| government_type                = [[Federal monarchy|Federal]] [[constitutional monarchy]]\n| title_representative                = [[Regent|Regency of the Mexican Empire]]\n| representative1                = [[Juan Almonte]], [[Jos\u00e9 Mariano Salas|Jos\u00e9 Salas]], [[Pelagio Antonio de Labastida y D\u00e1valos|Pelagio de Labastida]]\n| year_representative1                = 1863\u20131864\n| title_leader                = [[Emperor of Mexico|Emperor]]\n| leader1                = [[Maximilian I of Mexico|Maximilian I]]\n| year_leader1                = 1864\u20131867\n| religion                = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| event_pre                = [[Second French intervention in Mexico|Second French Intervention]]\n| date_pre                = 8 December 1861\n| event_start                = Maximilian I accepts Mexican crown\n| date_start                = 10 April\n| event_end                = Emperor Maximilian I executed\n| date_end                = 19 June\n| currency                = [[Mexican peso|Peso]]\n| today                = [[Mexico]]\n| deputy3                = [[Santiago Vidaurri]]\n| title_deputy                = [[President of the Council of Ministers of the Mexican Empire|Prime Minister]]<ref>Covarruvias Jos\u00e9, Enciclopedia Pol\u00edtica de M\u00e9xico, TOMO IV, Edit. Belisario Dom\u00ednguez. 2010</ref>\n| year_deputy2                = 1866\u20131867\n| deputy2                = [[Teodosio Lares]]\n| year_deputy1                = 1864\u20131866\n| deputy1                = [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Lacunza]]\n| area_km2                = \n| HDI_year                = \n| HDI                = \n| GDP_PPP_year                = \n| GDP_PPP                = \n| area_rank                = \n| demonym                = \n| year_deputy3                = 1867\n}}\n\nThe '''Mexican Empire''' ({{lang-es|Imperio Mexicano}}) or '''Second Mexican Empire''' ({{lang-es|Segundo Imperio Mexicano}}) was the name of [[Mexico]] under a constitutional hereditary monarchy declared by a Mexican Assembly of Notables in accordance with the interests of the [[Second French Empire|French Empire]], during the [[Second French intervention in Mexico]]. [[Napoleon III of France]] wanted to establish a monarchist ally in the Americas as a restraint upon the growing power of the [[United States]] <ref>{{cite book |last=Guedalla|first=Philip |date=1923|title=The Second Empire |location= |publisher=Hodder and Stoughton |page=322 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref>. Chosen as the Mexican emperor was Austrian Archduke [[Maximilian I of Mexico|Ferdinand Maximilian]], of the [[House of Habsburg-Lorraine]].\n\nPromoted by the powerful and conservative elite of Mexico's \"[[Hacienda|hacendado]]s\", with the support of the French, as well as from the [[Austrian Empire|Austrian]] and [[Belgian monarchy|Belgian]] crowns, the intervention attempted to create a monarchical system in Mexico, as it had functioned during the 300 years of the viceroyalty of [[New Spain]] and for the short term of the imperial independent reign of Emperor [[Agust\u00edn de Iturbide|Agust\u00edn I]] of Mexico. The French attempt to establish a monarchy however triggered a civil war in Mexico, with the imperialists ultimately losing soon after the French troops withdrew from the country. The Empire came to an end on June 19, 1867, with the execution of Emperor Maximilian I by the government of the restored Mexican Republic. \n\n==History==\n{{Main|Second French intervention in Mexico}}\n\n===Mexican Monarchism===\nMexican monarchism emerged in conjunction with the struggle for independence. After [[Napoleon|Napoleon Bonaparte]] invaded Spain, the initial independence movements throughout Latin America concerned themselves with supporting the deposed [[Ferdinand VII of Spain|Ferdinand VII]] as the legitimate king as opposed to [[Joseph Bonaparte]] who had been established as king of Spain by Napoleon. During the [[Cry of Dolores|Grito de Dolores]], Miguel Hidalgo Costilla rallied his listeners to support Ferdinand VII against the [[New Spain|New Spanish]] ruling classes that were allegedly going to betray Mexico and Catholicism over to the French. \n<ref>{{cite book |last=Fehrenbach|first=T.R. |date=1995|title=Fire and Blood: A History of Mexico |url=https://archive.org/details/firebloodhistory00fehr_0|url-access=registration|location= |publisher=Da Capo Press |page=[https://archive.org/details/firebloodhistory00fehr_0/page/320 320] |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref>\n\nWhile his insurrection was unsuccessful the ultimate triumphant movement for Mexican independence was led by Agustin de Iturbide with his [[Plan of Iguala]], which made specific admission for a European monarch to be placed on the Mexican throne. After the offer was refused Iturbide himself assumed the throne in a barracks revolt, which was nonetheless confirmed by the Mexican congress.\n\nIturbide in his attempts to govern became increasingly autocratic, losing support of congress, and shutting the legislature down, discrediting monarchy even amongst conservatives, but the idea did not go away. In 1838, [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Guti\u00e9rrez de Estrada|Jose Maria Gutierrez Estrada]] wrote a monarchist essay endorsing the idea of a legitimate European monarch being invited to govern Mexico. The pamphlet was addressed to the conservative president [[Anastasio Bustamante|Bustamante]], who rejected the idea.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bancroft|first=Hubert Howe |date=1852|title=History of Mexico Vol 5 |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofmexico05banc |location= |publisher=The Bancroft Company |pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofmexico05banc/page/224 224]\u2013225|isbn= |author-link= }}</ref>\n\n===Role of France===\n[[File:Comisi\u00f3n_Mexicana_en_Miramar.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Mexican Delegation: '''Back Row''': [[:es:Jos\u00e9 Manuel Hidalgo y Esnaurr\u00edzar|Jos\u00e9 Hidalgo]], [[:es:Antonio Escand\u00f3n| Antonio Escand\u00f3n]], [[\u00c1ngel Dom\u00ednguez]], [[Antonio Peredo]], [[Adrian Woll]], [[Jose Maria de Landa]]. '''Front Row''': [[:es:Ignacio Aguilar y Marocho|Ignacio Marocho]], [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Guti\u00e9rrez de Estrada]], [[:es:Francisco Javier Miranda y Morfi|Francisco Morfi]], [[:es:Joaqu\u00edn Vel\u00e1zquez de Le\u00f3n|Joaqu\u00edn de Le\u00f3n]]]]\n\nHeavily influenced by his wife Empress [[Eug\u00e9nie de Montijo|Eugenie]], who was in contact with the aforementioned [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Guti\u00e9rrez de Estrada|Estrada]] and his fellow Mexican monarchist  [[:es:Jos\u00e9 Manuel Hidalgo y Esnaurr\u00edzar|Jos\u00e9 Hidalgo]], [[Napoleon III]] became intent on reviving the Mexican monarchy. Prior to 1861 any interference in the affairs of Mexico by European powers would have been viewed in the U.S as a challenge to the [[Monroe Doctrine]]. In 1861 however, the U.S. was embroiled in its own conflict, the [[American Civil War]], which made the U.S. government powerless to intervene. When on July, 1861 Mexican President [[Benito Juarez]] declared a two-year moratorium on Mexican debt to France among other nations, Napoleon finally had a pretext. Encouraged by Empress Eugenie, who saw herself as the champion of the Catholic Church in Mexico, Napoleon III took advantage of the situation.\n\n[[File:Dell'Acqua Ernennung Maximilians zum Kaiser Mexikos.jpg|thumb|right|350px|The Offering of the Mexican Crown by a Mexican delegation, [[Miramare Castle]], 1863.]]\n\nNapoleon III saw the opportunity to make France the great modernizing influence in the Western Hemisphere, as well as enabling the country to capture the [[South American]] markets. To give him further encouragement, there was his half brother, the [[Charles de Morny, Duke of Morny|duc de Morny]], who was the largest holder of [[Mexico|Mexican]] bonds.\n\nFrench troops landed in December, 1861, and began military operations on April, 1862. They were eventually joined by conservative Mexican generals who had never been entirely defeated in the  [[Reform War|War of Reform]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Bancroft |first=Hubert Howe |date=1887 |title=History of Mexico Volume VI 1861-1887|location=San Francisco |publisher=The History Company |page=[https://archive.org/details/worksofhuberthow14bancrich/page/51 51]|url=https://archive.org/details/worksofhuberthow14bancrich}}</ref> After [[Charles de Lorencez]] small expeditionary force was repulsed at the [[Battle of Puebla]], reinforcements were sent and placed under the command of [[\u00c9lie Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Forey|\u00c9lie Forey]]. The capital was taken by June, 1863 and the French now sought to establish a friendly Mexican government. Forey appointed a committee of thirty five Mexicans, the ''Junta Superior'' who then elected three Mexican citizens to serve as the government's executive: [[Juan Almonte|Juan Nepucemo Almonte]], [[Jos\u00e9 Mariano Salas]], and [[Pelagio Antonio de Labastida y D\u00e1valos|Pelagio Antonio de Labastida]]. In turn this triumvirate then selected two hundred fifteen Mexican citizens to form together with the ''Junta Superior'', an ''Assembly of Notables''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bancroft |first=Hubert Howe |date=1887 |title=History of Mexico Volume VI 1861-1887|location=San Francisco |publisher=The History Company |pages=[https://archive.org/details/worksofhuberthow14bancrich/page/77 77]\u201378|url=https://archive.org/details/worksofhuberthow14bancrich}}</ref>\n\nThe Assembly met on July, 1863 and resolved to invite Ferdinand Maximilian to be Emperor of Mexico. The executive triumvirate was formally changed into the Regency of the Mexican Empire. An official delegation left Mexico and arrived in Europe on October. Maximilian formally accepted the crown on April 10, 1864, and set sail for Mexico, arriving in [[Veracruz]] on May 28 and reaching the capital on June 12.\n\n===Maximilian's Reign=== \nOn his arrival in the summer of 1864 Maximilian declared a political amnesty for all liberals who wished to join the Empire, and his conciliation efforts eventually won over moderate liberals such as [[Jos\u00e9 Fernando Ram\u00edrez]] and [[Santiago Vidaurri]] <ref>{{cite book |last=Bancroft|first=Hubert Howe |date=1888|title=History of Mexico Volume VI 1861-1887|location= |publisher=The Bancroft Company |pages=150}}</ref>. His first priorities included reforming his ministries and reforming the Imperial Mexican Army, the latter of which was impeded upon by [[Fran\u00e7ois Achille Bazaine|Bazaine]] in an effort to consolidate French control of the nation.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bancroft|first=Hubert Howe |date=1888|title=History of Mexico Volume VI 1861-1887 |location= |publisher=The Bancroft Company |pages=152}}</ref>\n\nOn August, Maximilian took a state trip through the nation while [[Carlota of Mexico|Carlota]] reigned as regent, going to [[Queretaro]], [[Guanajuato]], and [[Michoacan]], giving public audiences and visiting officials, even celebrating Mexican independence by commemorating the [[Cry of Dolores]], in the actual town where it took place. <ref>{{cite book |last=Bancroft|first=Hubert Howe |date=1888|title=History of Mexico Volume VI 1861-1887 |location= |publisher=The Bancroft Company |pages=154-155}}</ref> \n\nIn December a Papal Nuncio arrived in order to arrange a concordat with the Empire revise the [[La Reforma|Reform laws]] previously passed by the Mexican government that had nationalized Catholic Church property. Maximilian wished to maintain Catholicism as the state religion, and yet preferred to keep the reform laws intact, and also introduce religious toleration, measures which disillusioned his conservative and clerical supporters <ref>{{cite book |last=Bancroft|first=Hubert Howe |date=1888|title=History of Mexico Volume VI 1861-1887 | |location= |publisher=The Bancroft Company |pages=157-158}}</ref>.\n\n===Military Hostilities===\n\nIn April 1865, the [[American Civil War|U.S. Civil War]] ended, and while the American government was reluctant at the time to enter upon a conflict with France to enforce the Monroe Doctrine, official American sympathy remained with the deposed Mexican president [[Benito Ju\u00e1rez]]. The U.S. government refused to recognize the Empire and also ignored Maximilian's correspondence.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bancroft|first=Hubert Howe |date=1888|title=History of Mexico Volume VI 1861-1887| |location= |publisher=The Bancroft Company |pages=181}}</ref> In December, a thirty million dollar private American loan was approved for Juarez, and American volunteers kept joining the Mexican republican troops.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bancroft|first=Hubert Howe |date=1888|title=History of Mexico Volume VI 1861-1887|location= |publisher=The Bancroft Company |pages=206-207}}</ref>\n\nA concentration of French troops in the north of Mexico only led to a surge of republican guerilla activity in the south. While French troops controlled major cities, guerillas continued to be a major military threat in the countryside. In an effort to combat the increasing violence and in a belief that Juarez was outside of the nation already, Maximilian in October signed a decree authorizing the court martial and execution of anyone found either aiding or participating with the guerillas. The harsh measure was hardly unprecedented in Mexican history even resembling an 1862 measure by Juarez, but it proved to be widely reviled, being branded the Black Decree, and contributing to the growing unpopularity of the Empire <ref>{{cite book |last=Bancroft|first=Hubert Howe |date=1888|title=History of Mexico Volume VI 1861-1887 ||location= |publisher=The Bancroft Company |pages=183-184}}</ref>.\n\n===Fall of the Empire===\n\nIn January 1866, seeing the war as unwinnable Napoleon declared to the French Chambers that he intended to withdraw the French military from Mexico. Maximilian's request for more aid or at least a delay in troop withdrawals was denied. Carlota arrived in Europe in an attempt to plead for the Empire's cause, but was unable to gain more support. The failure of her mission apparently caused her to go insane. \n\nIn October Maximilian moved his cabinet to [[Orizaba]] and was widely rumored to be leaving the nation. He contemplated abdication, and on November 25 held a council of his ministers to address the crisis faced by the Empire. They narrowly voted against abdication and Maximilian headed back towards the capital. <ref>{{cite book |last=Bancroft|first=Hubert Howe |date=1888|title=History of Mexico Volume VI 1861-1887|location= |publisher=The Bancroft Company |pages=241}}</ref> He intended to appeal to the nation in order to hold a national assembly which would then decide what form of government the Mexican nation was to take. Such a measure however would require a ceasefire from Juarez who had no such intention of conceding to what he viewed as a usurper. \n\nAs the national assembly project fell through Maximilian decided to focus on military operations and in February as the last of the French troops were leaving, the Emperor headed for the city of [[Quer\u00e9taro City|Queretaro]] to join the bulk of his loyal Mexican troops, numbering about 10,000 men. The liberal generals [[Mariano Escobedo|Escobedo]] and [[Ram\u00f3n Corona|Corona]] converged on Queretaro with 40,000 men and yet the city held out until being betrayed by an imperial officer who opened the gates to the liberals on May 15. <ref>{{cite book |last=Fehrenbach|first=T.R. |date=1995|title=Fire and Blood: A History of Mexico |url= |location= |publisher=Da Capo Press |page=438 }}</ref>\n\nMaximilian was captured and placed on trial with his leading generals [[Tom\u00e1s Mej\u00eda Camacho|Mej\u00eda]] and [[Miguel Miram\u00f3n|Miramon]]. All there were sentenced to death and executed on June 19.\n\n==Government==\n[[File:ImperialMexicanCrown1.jpg|thumb|right|175px|The Mexican [[imperial crown]] and [[scepter]] as [[funerary]] insignia. Wood, gilded, pearl and stone imitation. around 1867, Imperial [[Furniture]] [[Depot]], [[Vienna]].]]\n\nA provisional constitution was issued in 1865. The emperor was to govern through nine ministries: of the Imperial Household, of State, of Foreign Relations, of War, of Government or Interior, of the Treasury, of Justice, of Public Instruction and Worship, and of Development. A council of state was given the power to frame bills and give advice to the emperor, and a separate private cabinet, serving as the emperor's liaison, was divided into civil and military affairs. [[Carlota of Mexico|Empress Carlota]] was given the right to serve as regent if under certain circumstances Maximilian was to be unavailable.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bancroft |first=Hubert Howe |date=1887 |title=History of Mexico Volume VI 1861-1887|location=San Francisco |publisher=The History Company |page=[https://archive.org/details/worksofhuberthow14bancrich/page/171 171]|url=https://archive.org/details/worksofhuberthow14bancrich}}</ref>\n\nDuring his short reign, Maximilian issued eight volumes of laws covering all aspects of government, including forest management, railroads, roads, canals, postal services, telegraphs, mining, and immigration.<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=La legislaci\u00f3n del Segundo Imperio |url=https://inehrm.gob.mx/work/models/inehrm/Resource/440/1/images/La-legislacion-del-Segundo-Imperio.pdf |language=Spanish|location= |publisher= |page=9 |date= |isbn=}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=McAllen |first=M.M |date=Jan 8, 2014 |title=Maximilian and Carlota: Europe\u2019s Last Empire in Mexico |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CkvpCAAAQBAJ&dq |location= |publisher=Trinity University Press |page=143 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref>\nThe emperor passed legislation guaranteeing equality before the law and freedom of speech, and laws meant to defend the rights of laborers, especially that of the Indians. Labor laws in Yucat\u00e1n actually became harsher on workers after the fall of the Empire.<ref>{{cite book |last=Richmond|first=Douglas W. |date=April 15, 2015 |title=Conflict and Carnage in Yucat\u00e1n: Liberals, the Second Empire, and Maya Revolutionaries, 1855\u20131876\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5KLLBgAAQBAJ |location= |publisher=University of Alabama Press |page=70 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref> A national system of free schools was also planned based on the German gymnasia and the emperor founded an academy of sciences and literature.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bancroft |first=Hubert Howe |date=1887 |title=History of Mexico Volume VI 1861-1887|location=San Francisco |publisher=The History Company |page=[https://archive.org/details/worksofhuberthow14bancrich/page/173 173]|url=https://archive.org/details/worksofhuberthow14bancrich}} </ref> Laws were published both in Spanish and in [[Nahuatl]], the Aztec language, and Maximilian appointed leading Nahuatl scholar [[Faustino Galicia]] as an advisor to his government.<ref>{{cite book |last=McAllen |first=M.M. |date= |title=Maximilian and Carlota: Europe\u2019s Last Empire in Mexico |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CkvpCAAAQBAJ&source=gbs_navlinks_s |location= |publisher=Trinity University Press |page=142 }}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n\n===Railways===\n[[File:13Puente_de_Metlac.png|thumb|left|250px|Mexican Railway, Bridge by [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Velasco G\u00f3mez]] 1877.]]\n\nOne of the main challenges encountered by the Emperor was the lack of sufficient infrastructure to link the different parts of the realm. The main goal was connecting the port of Veracruz and the capital in Mexico City. In 1857, Don Antonio Escand\u00f3n secured the right to build a line from the port of Veracruz to Mexico City and on to the [[Pacific Ocean]]. Revolution and political instability stifled progress on the financing or construction of the line until 1864, when, under the regime of [[Emperor Maximilian I of Mexico|Emperor Maximilian]], the Imperial Mexican Railway Company began construction of the line. Political upheaval continued to stifle progress, and the initial segment from Veracruz to Mexico City was inaugurated nine years later on January 1, 1873 by President [[Sebasti\u00e1n Lerdo de Tejada]].\n\n[[File:21Puente_de_Wimer-Cumbre_de_Maltrata.png|thumb|right|250px|Mexican Railway, Bridge by [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Velasco G\u00f3mez]] 1877.]]\n\nIn 1857 the original proprietors of the government concession, the Masso Brothers, inaugurated on the 4th of July the train service from Tlatelolco, in M\u00e9xico City, to the nearby town of [[Villa de Guadalupe, Mexico City|Guadalupe Hidalgo]].<ref>[http://www.fotolog.com/ahuicyani/77908717/ Ferrocarril de M\u00e9xico a La Villa]</ref> Eventually they ran out of funds and decided to sell it to Manuel Escand\u00f3n and Antonio Escand\u00f3n.<ref>[https://www.mexicodesconocido.com.mx/ferrocarril-ruta-vital.html La historia del tren en M\u00e9xico]</ref> The Escand\u00f3n Brothers continued working and the project, and Antonio Escand\u00f3n visited the United States and England in the last months of the year. In the first country, he hired Andrew Talcott, and in the latter, he sold company stock. Exploration of a route from Orizaba to Maltrata was performed by engineers Andrew H. Talcott and Pascual Almaz\u00e1n.\n\n[[File:14Orizaba_desde_el_Puente_de_Paso_del_Toro.png|thumb|left|250px|Mexican Railway, Bridge by [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Velasco G\u00f3mez]] 1877.]]\n[[File:Jos\u00e9_Mar\u00eda_Velasco_-_The_Metlac_Ravine_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Velasco - The Metlac Ravine.]]\n\nDuring the French intervention, part of the railways were destroyed. The only option available was the establishment of a pact between the French Army, and the two companies of the Escand\u00f3n Brothers. The French Army was to provide a subsidy to the companies of 120 000 francs a month for the works, and the companies were to establish service from Veracruz to Soledad para by May, actually concluding on August 15, 1862, concluding 41 kilometres of tracks. Next they reached the Camar\u00f3n station, with a length of 62 kilometres. By October 16, 1864 they reached Paso del Macho with a length of 76 kilometres.<ref>Chapman, John Gresham, La construcci\u00f3n del Ferrocarril Mexicano, 1985</ref>\n\nOn September 19, 1864, the Imperial Mexican Railway Company (Compa\u00f1\u00eda Limitada del Ferrocarril Imperial Mexicano) was Incorporated in London to complete the earlier projects and continued construction on this line. Escand\u00f3n ceded his privileges to the new company. Smith, Knight and Co. was later contracted in 1864 by the Imperial Mexican Railway to continue work on the line from Mexico City to Veracruz.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/railroadsmexico00powegoog The Railroads of Mexico]</ref> William Elliot was employed as Chief Assistant for three years on the construction of about 70 miles of the heaviest portion of the Mexican Railway, after which he returned to England. He had several years of experience building railways in England, India, and Brazil. In this last country, he held the position of Engineer-in-Chief of the Province of S\u00e3o Paulo.<ref>[https://www.gracesguide.co.uk/William_Elliot_(1827-1892) William Elliot (1827-1892)] Grace's Guide to British Industrial History</ref>\n\nMaximiliano I hired engineer M Lyons for the construction of the line from La Soledad to Monte del Chiquihuite, later on joining the line from Veracruz to Paso del Macho.<ref>[http://www.ferrodemex.com.mx/historia.php Historia del Ferrocarril]</ref> Works were begun in Maltrata, at the same time that the works from Veracruz and Mexico City kept moving forward. By the end of the Empire in June 1867, 76 kilometers from Veracruz to Paso del Macho were functional (part of the concession to Lyons) and the line from Mexico City reached Apizaco with 139&nbsp;km.<ref>[[:es:Ferrosur]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=January 2018}}\n\n===Banking===\n[[File:Monumento a Col\u00f3n Paseo de la Reforma Ciudad de M\u00e9xico.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Maximillian planned the monument to [[Christopher Columbus]] for the grand boulevard, now called [[Paseo de la Reforma]]. It was built during the regime of [[Porfirio D\u00edaz]].]]\n\nBefore 1864, there was no banking in Mexico. Credits were obtained from religious orders and merchant guilds. During the French Intervention, the branch of a British bank was opened. The London Bank of Mexico and South America Ltd began operations with a capital of two and a half million pesos. It belonged to the Baring Brothers Group, and had its head office in the corner of the Capuchinas and Lerdo Streets in Downtown Mexico City.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com.mx/brand-voice/banco-londres-mexico-sudamerica-primer-banco-comercial-mexico/ Banco de Londres, M\u00e9xico y Sudam\u00e9rica, el primer banco comercial de M\u00e9xico] Forbes</ref>\n\n===Foreign Trade===\nAt the beginning of the [[American Civil War]], the city of [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]] was simply a sleepy little border town across the Rio Grande from Brownsville.<ref>{{cite book| last=Delaney|first=Robert W.| title=Matamoros, Port for Texas during the Civil War| year=1955| publisher=Texas State Historical Association| issn=0038-478X| page=487| jstor=30241907}}</ref> It had, for several years, been considered a port, but it had relatively few ships arriving. Previous to the war, accounts mention that not over six ships entered the port each year.<ref name=\"United States. War Dept\">{{cite book|title=The War of the Rebellion: a Compilation of the Official Records of the Union and Confederate Armies|year=1880\u20131901|publisher=United States. War Dept.|location=Washington|jstor=30241907}}</ref> Nevertheless, in about four years, Matamoros, due to its proximity to Texas, was to assume state as a port, and multiply its inhabitants in number. Following is a quote from a Union General in 1885 describing the importance of the port in Matamoros:\n\n{{quote|Matamoros is to the rebellion west of the Mississippi what New York is to the United States\u2014its great commercial and financial center, feeding and clothing the rebellion, arming and equipping, furnishing it materials of war and a specie basis of circulation that has almost displaced Confederate paper...The entire Confederate Government is greatly sustained by resources from this port.<ref>{{cite book|last=Underwood|first=Rodman L.|title=Waters of Discord: The Union Blockade of Texas During the Civil War|year=2008|publisher=McFarland|page=200|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QxywnKkZSlYC&pg=PA72&lpg=PA72&dq=matamoros+is+to+the+rebellion+west#v=onepage&q=matamoros%20is%20to%20the%20rebellion%20west&f=false|isbn=9780786437764}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Emperor_Maximiliano_around_1865.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Emperor Don Maximiliano I of Mexico (1832-1867).]]\n\nThe cotton trade brought together in [[Bagdad, Tamaulipas]] and Matamoros over 20,000 speculators from the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] and the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]], England, France, and Germany.<ref>{{cite news|title=Matamoros|jstor=30241907|newspaper=New Orleans Times|date=1 June 1865}}</ref> Bagdad had grown from a small, seashore town to a \"full-pledge town.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=New York Herald|jstor=30241907|date=9 January 1865}}</ref> The English-speaking population in the area by 1864 was so great that Matamoros even had a newspaper printed in English\u2014it was called the ''Matamoros Morning Call''.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Southwestern Historical Quarterly|url=http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth101158/m1/567/|newspaper=New Orleans Daily True Delta|date=16 December 1864}}</ref> In addition, the port exported cotton to England and France, where millions of people needed it for their daily livelihood,<ref>{{cite book|title=Official Records of the War of the Rebellion|year=1894\u20131922|publisher=United States Department of War|location=Washington|jstor=30241907}}</ref> and it was possible to receive fifty cents per pound in gold for cotton, when it cost about three cents in the Confederacy, \"and much more money was received for it laid down in New York and European ports.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Henry|first=Robert S.|title=The State of the Confederacy|date=22 August 1989|publisher=Da Capo Paperback|location=New York|page=342|jstor=30241907}}</ref> Other sources mention that the port of Matamoros traded with London, [[Havana]], [[Belize]], and [[New Orleans]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Matamoros and Belize: \"From powder and caps to a needle\"|jstor=30241907|newspaper=New Orleans Times|date=12 November 1864}}</ref><ref>{{citebook|last=Hanna|first=Alfred J.|title=The Immigration Movement of the Intervention and Empire as Seen Through the Mexican Press|date=May 1947|publisher=The Hispanic American Historical Review|location=Duke University|page=246|jstor=2508417}}</ref> The Matamoros and New York City trade agreement, however, continued throughout the war and until 1864, and it was considered \"heavy and profitable.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Matamoros and New York: Heavy and profitable|jstor=30241907|newspaper=New Orleans Era|date=1 November 1864}}</ref>\n\nBy 1865, Matamoros was described as a prosperous town of 30,000 people,<ref>{{cite news|title=Matamoros port: 30,000 inhabitants|jstor=30241907|newspaper=New Orleans Times|date=3 March 1865}}</ref>  and [[Lew Wallace]] informed General [[Ulysses S. Grant]] that neither [[Baltimore]] or [[New Orleans]] could compare itself to the growing commercial activity of Matamoros.<ref name=\"United States. War Dept\"/> Nevertheless, after the collapse of the Confederacy, \"gloom, despondency, and despair\" became evident in Matamoros\u2014markets shut down, business almost ceased to exist, and ships were rarely seen.<ref>{{cite news|title=Port of Matamoros: \"gloom, despondency, and despair\"|newspaper=New York Herald|date=17 March 1865}}</ref> \"For Sale\" signs began to sprout up everywhere, and Matamoros returned to its role of a sleepy little border town across the [[Rio Grande]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Port of Matamoros|jstor=30241907|newspaper=New Orleans Times|date=1 June 1865}}</ref>\n\nThe conclusion of the [[American Civil War]] brought a severe crisis to the now abandoned Port of Bagdad, a crisis that until this day the port has never recovered from.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Journal of Southern History|date=November 1984|publisher=Southern Historical Association|issn=0022-4642|jstor=2208496}}</ref> In addition, a tremendous hurricane in 1889 destroyed the desolated port. This same hurricane was one of the many hurricanes during the period of devastating hurricanes of 1870 to 1889, which reduced the population of Matamoros to nearly half its size, mounting with it another upsetting economic downturn.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schober|first=Otto|title=Cuando el r\u00edo Bravo era navegable|url=http://www.zocalo.com.mx/seccion/opinion-articulo/cuando-el-rio-bravo-era-navegable|newspaper=Z\u00f3calo Saltillo}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Beezley|first=William H.|title=A Companion to Mexican History and Culture|year=2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=1-4443-4057-3|pages=688|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BrdWgkSG_HMC&pg=PA323&dq=matamoros,+tamaulipas#v=onepage&q=matamoros%2C%20tamaulipas&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==Territorial division==\n[[File:Political divisions of Mexico 1865 (location map scheme).svg|thumb|right|280px<!--should match infobox above-->|Departments of the Second Mexican Empire.]]\n\nMaximilian I wanted to reorganize the territory following scientific criteria, instead of following historical ties, traditional allegiances and the interests of local groups. The task of designing this new division was given to [[Manuel Orozco y Berra]].\n\nThis task was realized according to the following criteria: \n* The territory should be divided in at least fifty departments, \n* Whenever possible, natural boundaries shall be preferred, \n* For the territorial extension of each department, the configuration of the terrain, climate and elements of production were taken into consideration so that in due time, they could have a roughly equal number of inhabitants.<ref>Rub\u00e9n Garc\u00eda, \"Biograf\u00eda, bibliograf\u00eda e iconograf\u00eda de don Manuel Orozco y Berra\", en Bolet\u00edn de la Sociedad Mexicana de Geograf\u00eda y Estad\u00edstica, M\u00e9xico, Compa\u00f1\u00eda Editora e Impresora \"La Afici\u00f3n\", 1934, p. 233.</ref>\n\nOn March 13, 1865, the new Law on the territorial division of the Mexican Empire was published.<ref>[http://www.agn.gob.mx/menuprincipal/difusion/textos/pdf/DiarioImperio13mar1865.pdf Diario del Imperio, Tomo I N\u00famero 59, 13 de marzo de 1865]</ref> The Empire was divided into 50 departments, though not every department was ever able to be administered due to the ongoing war.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ '''Population by department'''\n! Number\n! Department\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Total population\n! Capital\n! Prefect<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Almanaque Imperial para el a\u00f1o de 1866 |url=http://cdigital.dgb.uanl.mx/la/1020005252/1020005252_MA.PDF |location= |publisher=J.M. Lara |pages=57\u201368 |date=1866 |isbn=}}</ref>\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Population\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Surface (Sq Leagues)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Pop. Density\n|- \n| XXL\n| [[Acapulco Department|Acapulco]]\n| align=\"right\" | 97,949\n| align=\"right\" | [[Acapulco]]\n| align=\"right\" | \n| align=\"right\" | 3,000\n| align=\"right\" | 1,965\n| align=\"right\" | 49.85\n|- \n| XXX\n| [[Aguascalientes Department|Aguascalientes]]\n| align=\"right\" | 433,151\n| align=\"right\" | [[Aguascalientes City|Aguascalientes]]\n| align=\"right\" | Francisco R. de Esparza\n| align=\"right\" | 23,000\n| align=\"right\" | 1,768\n| align=\"right\" | 244.99\n|- \n| XLIV\n| [[\u00c1lamos Department|\u00c1lamos]]\n| align=\"right\" | 41,041\n| align=\"right\" | [[\u00c1lamos]]\n| align=\"right\" |\n| align=\"right\" | 6,000\n| align=\"right\" | 2,657\n| align=\"right\" | 15.45\n|- \n| XLVI\n| [[Arizona (department)|Arizona]]\n| align=\"right\" | 25,603\n| align=\"right\" | [[Altar, Sonora|Altar]]\n| align=\"right\" | Jos\u00e9 Moreno Bustamante\n| align=\"right\" | 1,000\n| 